<?xml version="1.0"?>
<rdf:RDF xmlns="urn:absolute:h/"
     xml:base="urn:absolute:h/"
     xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#"
     xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
     xmlns:www="http://www.cair.za.net/"
     xmlns:xml="http://www.w3.org/XML/1998/namespace"
     xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#"
     xmlns:cair="http://cair.za.net/"
     xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
     xmlns:terms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/"
     xmlns:defeasible="http://cair.za.net/defeasible#">
    <owl:Ontology rdf:about="http://victoriachama.org/net/AccessControlPolicyOntology">
        <owl:versionIRI rdf:resource="http://victoriachama.org/net/AccessControlPolicyOntology/1.0.0"/>
        <cair:consistent rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean">true</cair:consistent>
        <terms:license rdf:resource="https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0"/>
        <rdfs:comment>This ontology provides a formal representation of access control and policy mechanisms within organizational, governmental, and computational domains. It captures entities such as agents, employees, systems, and resources, along with the permissions, prohibitions, authorizations, and contextual constraints that regulate access.

The ontology is designed within a defeasible reasoning framework, acknowledging that access control policies are rarely absolute. Rules typically confer rights or impose restrictions, yet they may be subject to exceptions, priority relations, and overriding conditions. For example, general access permissions can be suspended by judicial injunctions, presidential waivers, or emergency overrides.

By encoding both default rules and their exceptions, the ontology supports non-monotonic inference over access control scenarios. This enables reasoning not only about what is normally permissible, but also about cases where higher-priority rules or situational contexts alter default outcomes. Such modeling enhances the expressive power of access control ontologies, allowing for a more realistic treatment of complex policy domains.</rdfs:comment>
    </owl:Ontology>
    


